# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: wave-optics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In optics, a **diffraction grating** is a grating with a periodic structure of appropriate scale so as to diffract light, or another type of electromagnetic radiation, into several beams traveling in different directions (i.e., different diffraction angles) known as diffracted orders.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The emerging coloration is a form of structural coloration.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The directions or diffraction angles of these beams depend on the wave (light) incident angle to the diffraction grating, the spacing or periodic distance between adjacent diffracting elements (e.g., parallel slits for a transmission grating) on the grating, and the wavelength of the incident light.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Because the grating acts as a dispersive element, diffraction gratings are commonly used in monochromators and spectrometers, but other applications are also possible such as optical encoders for high-precision motion control and wavefront measurement.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] For typical applications, a reflective grating has ridges or "rulings" on its surface while a transmissive grating has transmissive or hollow slits on its surface.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Such a grating modulates the amplitude of an incident wave to create a diffraction pattern.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Some gratings modulate the phases of incident waves rather than the amplitude, and these types of gratings can be produced frequently by using holography.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] James Gregory (1638–1675) observed the diffraction patterns caused by a bird feather, which was effectively the first diffraction grating (in a natural form) to be discovered, about a year after Isaac Newton's prism experiments.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The first human-made diffraction grating was made around 1785 by Philadelphia inventor David Rittenhouse, who strung hairs between two finely threaded screws.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This was similar to notable German physicist Joseph von Fraunhofer's wire diffraction grating in 1821.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The principles of diffraction were discovered by Thomas Young and Augustin-Jean Fresnel.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Using these principles, Fraunhofer was the first to use a diffraction grating to obtain line spectra and the first to measure the wavelengths of spectral lines with a diffraction grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In the 1860s, state-of-the-art diffraction gratings with small groove period, d , were manufactured by Friedrich Adolph Nobert (1806–1881) in Greifswald; then the two Americans Lewis Morris Rutherfurd (1816–1892) and William B.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] By the end of the 19th century, the concave gratings of Henry Augustus Rowland (1848–1901) were the best available.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A diffraction grating can create "rainbow" colors when it is illuminated by a wide-spectrum (e.g., continuous) light source.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Rainbow-like colors from closely spaced narrow tracks on optical data storage disks such as CDs or DVDs are an example of light diffraction caused by diffraction gratings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A usual diffraction grating has parallel lines (It is true for 1-dimensional gratings, but 2 or 3-dimensional gratings are also possible and they have their applications such as wavefront measurement), while a CD has a spiral of finely spaced data tracks.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction colors also appear when one looks at a bright point source through a translucent fine-pitch umbrella fabric covering.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Decorative patterned plastic films based on reflective grating patches are inexpensive and commonplace.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A similar color separation seen from thin layers of oil (or gasoline, etc.) on water, known as iridescence, is not caused by diffraction from a grating but rather by thin film interference from the closely stacked transmissive layers.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] For a diffraction grating, the relationship between the grating spacing (i.e., the distance between adjacent grating grooves or slits), the angle of the wave (light) incidence to the grating, and the diffracted wave from the grating is known as the grating equation.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Gratings may be of the 'reflective' or 'transmissive' type, analogous to a mirror or lens, respectively.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A grating has a 'zero-order mode' (where the integer order of diffraction m is set to zero), in which a ray of light behaves according to the laws of reflection (like a mirror) and refraction (like a lens), respectively.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] An idealized diffraction grating is made up of a set of slits of spacing d , that must be wider than the wavelength of interest to cause diffraction.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] As a result, the sum of the diffracted waves from the grating slits at the given observation point creates a peak, valley, or some degree between them in light intensity through additive and destructive interference.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Similarly, when the path difference is a multiple of ⁠ $\lambda$ ⁠, the waves are in phase and the (locally) maximum intensity occurs.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Various sign conventions for ⁠ $\theta _{i}$ ⁠, $\theta _{m}$ and m are used; any choice is fine as long as the choice is kept through diffraction-related calculations.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The diffracted light that corresponds to direct transmission for a transmissive diffraction grating or specular reflection for a reflective grating is called the zero order, and is denoted ⁠ $m=0$ ⁠.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The other diffracted light intensity maxima occur at angles $\theta _{m}$ represented by non-zero integer diffraction orders ⁠ m ⁠.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Note that m can be positive or negative, corresponding to diffracted orders on both sides of the zero-order diffracted beam.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The detailed diffracted light property distribution (e.g., intensity) depends on the detailed structure of the grating elements as well as on the number of elements in the grating, but it always gives maxima in the directions given by the grating equation.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] An optical axis diffraction grating, in which the optical axis is spatially and periodically modulated, is also considered either a reflection or transmission phase diffraction grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The grating equation applies to all these gratings due to the same phase relationship between the diffracted waves from adjacent diffracting elements of the gratings, even if the detailed distribution of the diffracted wave property depends on the detailed structure of each grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Quantum electrodynamics (QED) offers another derivation of the properties of a diffraction grating in terms of photons as particles (at some level).
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] QED can be described intuitively with the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] As such it can model photons as potentially following all paths from a source to a final point, each path with a certain probability amplitude.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] These probability amplitudes can be represented as a complex number or equivalent vector—or, as Richard Feynman simply calls them in his book on QED, "arrows".
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] For the probability that a certain event will happen, one sums the probability amplitudes for all of the possible ways in which the event can occur, and then takes the square of the length of the result.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The probability amplitude for a photon from a monochromatic source to arrive at a certain final point at a given time, in this case, can be modeled as an arrow that spins rapidly until it is evaluated when the photon reaches its final point.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] One can then evaluate the probability amplitude at the photon's final point; next, one can integrate over all of these arrows (see vector sum), and square the length of the result to obtain the probability that this photon will reflect off the mirror in the pertinent fashion.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The times these paths take are what determines the angle of the probability amplitude arrow, as they can be said to "spin" at a constant rate (which is related to the frequency of the photon).
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The times of the paths near the classical reflection site of the mirror are nearly the same, so the probability amplitudes point in nearly the same direction—thus, they have a sizable sum.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Examining the paths towards the edges of the mirror reveals that the times of nearby paths are quite different from each other, and thus we wind up summing vectors that cancel out quickly.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] So, there is a higher probability that light will follow a near-classical reflection path than a path further out.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Thus, this lets light of the right frequency sum to a larger probability amplitude, and as such possess a larger probability of reaching the appropriate final point.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This particular description involves many simplifications: a point source, a "surface" that light can reflect off (thus neglecting the interactions with electrons) and so forth.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The biggest simplification is perhaps in the fact that the "spinning" of the probability amplitude arrows is actually more accurately explained as a "spinning" of the source, as the probability amplitudes of photons do not "spin" while they are in transit.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] We obtain the same variation in probability amplitudes by letting the time at which the photon left the source be indeterminate—and the time of the path now tells us when the photon would have left the source, and thus what the angle of its "arrow" would be.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] However, this model and approximation is a reasonable one to illustrate a diffraction grating conceptually.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Light of a different frequency may also reflect off the same diffraction grating, but with a different final point.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The wavelength dependence in the grating equation shows that the grating separates an incident polychromatic beam into its constituent wavelength components at different angles, i.e., it is angular dispersive.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Each wavelength of input beam spectrum is sent into a different direction, producing a rainbow of colors under white light illumination.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This is visually similar to the operation of a prism, although the mechanism is very different.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A prism refracts waves of different wavelengths at different angles due to their different refractive indices, while a grating diffracts different wavelengths at different angles due to interference at each wavelength.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The diffracted beams corresponding to consecutive orders may overlap, depending on the spectral content of the incident beam and the grating density.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The higher the spectral order, the greater the overlap into the next order.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The grating equation shows that the angles of the diffracted orders only depend on the grooves' period, and not on their shape.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] By controlling the cross-sectional profile of the grooves, it is possible to concentrate most of the diffracted optical energy in a particular order for a given wavelength.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The incident angle and wavelength for which the diffraction is most efficient (the ratio of the diffracted optical energy to the incident energy is the highest) are often called "blazing angle" and "blazing wavelength".
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The efficiency of a grating may also depend on the polarization of the incident light.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Gratings are usually designated by their "groove density", the number of grooves per unit length, usually expressed in grooves per millimeter (g/mm), also equal to the inverse of the groove period.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The groove period must be on the order of the wavelength of interest; the spectral range covered by a grating is dependent on groove spacing and is the same for ruled and holographic gratings with the same grating constant (meaning *groove density* or the groove period).
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The maximum wavelength that a grating can diffract is equal to twice the grating period, in which case the incident and diffracted light are at ninety degrees (90°) to the grating normal.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] To obtain frequency dispersion over a wider frequency one must use a prism.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The optical regime, in which the use of gratings is most common, corresponds to wavelengths between 100 nm and 10 μm.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In that case, the groove density can vary from a few tens of grooves per millimeter, as in echelle gratings, to a few thousands of grooves per millimeter.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] When groove spacing is less than half the wavelength of light, the only present order is the *m* = 0 order.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Gratings with such small periodicity (with respect to the incident light wavelength) are called subwavelength gratings and exhibit special optical properties.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Made on an isotropic material the subwavelength gratings give rise to form birefringence, in which the material behaves as if it were birefringent.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Semiconductor technology today is also used to etch holographically patterned gratings into robust materials such as fused silica.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In this way, low stray-light holography is combined with the high efficiency of deep, etched transmission gratings, and can be incorporated into high-volume, low-cost semiconductor manufacturing technology.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Another method for manufacturing diffraction gratings uses a photosensitive gel sandwiched between two substrates.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A holographic interference pattern exposes the gel, which is later developed.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] These gratings, called ***volume-phase holography diffraction gratings*** (or ***VPH diffraction gratings***) have no physical grooves, but instead a periodic modulation of the refractive index within the gel.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This removes much of the surface scattering effects typically seen in other types of gratings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] These gratings also tend to have higher efficiencies, and allow for the inclusion of complicated patterns into a single grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A VPH diffraction grating is typically a transmission grating, through which incident light passes and is diffracted, but a VPH reflection grating can also be made by tilting the direction of a refractive index modulation with respect to the grating surface.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In older versions of such gratings, environmental susceptibility was a trade-off, as the gel had to be contained at low temperature and humidity.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Typically, the photosensitive substances are sealed between two substrates that make them resistant to humidity, and thermal and mechanical stresses.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] VPH diffraction gratings are not destroyed by accidental touches and are more scratch resistant than typical relief gratings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A blazed grating is manufactured with grooves that have a sawtooth-shaped cross section, unlike the symmetrical grooves of other gratings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This allows the grating to achieve maximum diffraction efficiency, but in only one diffraction order which is dependent on the angle of the sawtooth grooves, known as the blaze angle.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Common uses include specific wavelength selection for tunable lasers, among others.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] A new technology for grating insertion into integrated photonic lightwave circuits is **digital planar holography** (**DPH**).
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] DPH gratings are generated in computer and fabricated on one or several interfaces of an optical waveguide planar by using standard micro-lithography or nano-imprinting methods, compatible with mass-production.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Light propagates inside the DPH gratings, confined by the refractive index gradient, which provides longer interaction path and greater flexibility in light steering.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction gratings are often used in monochromators, spectrometers, lasers, wavelength division multiplexing devices, optical pulse compressing devices, interferometers, and many other optical instruments.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Ordinary pressed CD and DVD media are every-day examples of diffraction gratings and can be used to demonstrate the effect by reflecting sunlight off them onto a white wall.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This is a side effect of their manufacture, as one surface of a CD has many small pits in the plastic, arranged in a spiral; that surface has a thin layer of metal applied to make the pits more visible.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The structure of a DVD is optically similar, although it may have more than one pitted surface, and all pitted surfaces are inside the disc.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Due to the sensitivity to the refractive index of the media, diffraction grating can be used as sensor of fluid properties.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] In a standard pressed vinyl record when viewed from a low angle perpendicular to the grooves, a similar but less defined effect to that in a CD/DVD is seen.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This is due to viewing angle (less than the critical angle of reflection of the black vinyl) and the path of the light being reflected due to this being changed by the grooves, leaving a rainbow relief pattern behind.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction gratings are also used to distribute evenly the frontlight of e-readers such as the Nook Simple Touch with GlowLight.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Some everyday electronic components contain fine and regular patterns, and as a result readily serve as diffraction gratings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] For example, CCD sensors from discarded mobile phones and cameras can be removed from the device.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] With a laser pointer, diffraction can reveal the spatial structure of the CCD sensors.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] This can be done for LCD or LED displays of smart phones as well.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Because such displays are usually protected just by transparent casing, experiments can be done without damaging the phones.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] If accurate measurements are not intended, a spotlight can reveal the diffraction patterns.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Striated muscle is the most commonly found natural diffraction grating and, this has helped physiologists in determining the structure of such muscle.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Aside from this, the chemical structure of crystals can be thought of as diffraction gratings for types of electromagnetic radiation other than visible light, this is the basis for techniques such as X-ray crystallography.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Most commonly confused with diffraction gratings are the iridescent colors of peacock feathers, mother-of-pearl, and butterfly wings.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Iridescence in birds, fish and insects is often caused by thin-film interference rather than a diffraction grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction produces the entire spectrum of colors as the viewing angle changes, whereas thin-film interference usually produces a much narrower range.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The surfaces of flowers can also create a diffraction, but the cell structures in plants are usually too irregular to produce the fine slit geometry necessary for a diffraction grating.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The iridescence signal of flowers is thus only appreciable very locally and hence not visible to man and flower visiting insects.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] However, natural gratings do occur in some invertebrate animals, like the peacock spiders, the antennae of seed shrimp, and have even been discovered in Burgess Shale fossils.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction grating effects are sometimes seen in meteorology.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction coronas are colorful rings surrounding a source of light, such as the Sun.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] These are usually observed much closer to the light source than halos, and are caused by very fine particles, like water droplets, ice crystals, or smoke particles in a hazy sky.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] When the particles are all nearly the same size they diffract the incoming light at very specific angles.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] The exact angle depends on the size of the particles.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Diffraction coronas are commonly observed around light sources, like candle flames or street lights, in the fog.
[src:wave-optics/diffraction-grating] Cloud iridescence is caused by diffraction, occurring along coronal rings when the particles in the clouds are all uniform in size.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Photons or matter (like electrons) produce an interference pattern when two slits are used.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In modern physics, the **double-slit experiment** demonstrates that light and matter can exhibit behavior associated with both classical particles and classical waves.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This type of experiment was first described by Thomas Young in 1801 when making his case for the wave behavior of visible light.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1927, Davisson and Germer and, independently, George Paget Thomson and his research student Alexander Reid demonstrated that electrons show the same behavior, which was later extended to atoms and molecules.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The experiment belongs to a general class of "double path" experiments, in which two diffracted waves reconverge, creating an interference pattern.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Another version is the Mach–Zehnder interferometer, which splits the beam with a beam splitter.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In the basic version of this experiment, a coherent light source, such as a laser beam, illuminates a plate pierced by two parallel slits, and the light passing through the slits is observed on a screen behind the plate.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The wave nature of light causes the light waves passing through the two slits to interfere, producing bright and dark bands on the screen – a result that would not be expected if light consisted of classical particles.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] However, the light is always found to be absorbed at the screen at discrete points, as individual particles (not waves); the interference pattern appears via the varying density of these particle hits on the screen.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Furthermore, versions of the experiment that include detectors at the slits find that each detected photon passes through one slit (as would a classical particle), and not through both slits (as would a wave).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] However, such experiments demonstrate that particles do not form the interference pattern if one detects which slit they pass through.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] These results demonstrate the principle of wave–particle duality.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Other atomic-scale entities, such as electrons, are found to exhibit the same behavior when fired towards a double slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Additionally, the detection of individual discrete impacts is observed to be inherently probabilistic, which is inexplicable using classical mechanics.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The experiment can be done with entities much larger than electrons and photons, although it becomes more difficult as size increases.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The largest entities for which the double-slit experiment has been performed were molecules that each comprised 2000 atoms (whose total mass was 25,000 daltons).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The double-slit experiment (and its variations) has become a classic for its clarity in expressing the central puzzles of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Richard Feynman called it "a phenomenon which is impossible […] to explain in any classical way, and which has in it the heart of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If one illuminates two parallel slits, the light from the two slits again interferes.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Here the interference is a more pronounced pattern with a series of alternating light and dark bands.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The width of the bands is a property of the frequency of the illuminating light.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If light consisted strictly of ordinary or classical particles, and these particles were fired in a straight line through a slit and allowed to strike a screen on the other side, we would expect to see a pattern corresponding to the size and shape of the slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] However, when this "single-slit experiment" is actually performed, the pattern on the screen is a diffraction pattern in which the light is spread out.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The smaller the slit, the greater the angle of spread.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The top portion of the image shows the central portion of the pattern formed when a red laser illuminates a slit and, if one looks carefully, two faint side bands.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] More bands can be seen with a more highly refined apparatus.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The wave theory of light explains the pattern as being the result of the interference of light waves from the slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Feynman was fond of saying that all of quantum mechanics can be gleaned from carefully thinking through the implications of this single experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] He also proposed (as a thought experiment) that if detectors were placed before each slit, the interference pattern would disappear.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1801, Thomas Young presented a famous paper to the Royal Society entitled "On the Theory of Light and Colours" which explained interference phenomena like Newton's rings in terms of wave interference.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1803, Young followed up with demonstrations of optical interference using sunlight, pinholes and cards.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] These demonstrations played a crucial role in the understanding of the wave theory of light, challenging the corpuscular theory of light proposed by Isaac Newton, which had been the accepted model of light propagation in the 17th and 18th centuries.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] As part of his discussion of these experiments he describes a double slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] There is some question as to whether he ever actually performed a double-slit interference experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Later discovery of the photoelectric effect demonstrated that under different circumstances, light can behave as if it is composed of discrete particles.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] These seemingly contradictory discoveries, now called wave-particle duality, made it necessary to go beyond classical physics and take into account the quantum nature of light.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A low-intensity double-slit experiment was first performed by G.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Taylor in 1909, by reducing the level of incident light until photon emission/absorption events were mostly non-overlapping.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A slit interference experiment was not performed with anything other than light until 1961, when Claus Jönsson of the University of Tübingen performed it with coherent electron beams and multiple slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2002, the single-electron version of the experiment was voted "the most beautiful experiment" by readers of *Physics World.* Since that time a number of related experiments have been published, with a little controversy.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2012, Stefano Frabboni and co-workers sent single electrons onto nanofabricated slits (about 100 nm wide) and, by detecting the transmitted electrons with a single-electron detector, they could show the build-up of a double-slit interference pattern.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Many related experiments involving the coherent interference have been performed; they are the basis of modern electron diffraction, microscopy and high resolution imaging.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2018, single particle interference was demonstrated for antimatter in the Positron Laboratory (L-NESS, Politecnico di Milano) of Rafael Ferragut in Como (Italy), by a group led by Marco Giammarchi.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] An important version of this experiment involves single particle detection.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Illuminating the double-slit with a low intensity results in single particles being detected as white dots on the screen.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Remarkably, however, an interference pattern emerges when these particles are allowed to build up one by one (see the image below).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Final result of dot-by-dot build up of diffraction.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Across the middle of the image, the intensity alternates from high to low, showing interference in the signal from the two slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Movie of the pattern being built up dot by dot.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This phenomenon has been shown to occur with photons, electrons, atoms, and even some molecules: with buckminsterfullerene (C 60) in 2001, with 2 molecules of 430 atoms (C 60(C 12F 25) 10 and C 168H 94F 152O 8N 4S 4) in 2011, and with molecules of up to 2000 atoms in 2019.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In addition to interference patterns built up from single particles, up to 4 entangled photons can also show interference patterns.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The Mach–Zehnder interferometer can be seen as a simplified version of the double-slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Instead of propagating through free space after the two slits, and hitting any position in an extended screen, in the interferometer the photons can only propagate via two paths, and hit two discrete photodetectors.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This makes it possible to describe it via simple linear algebra in dimension 2, rather than differential equations.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A photon emitted by the laser hits the first beam splitter and is then in a superposition between the two possible paths.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In the second beam splitter these paths interfere, causing the photon to hit the photodetector on the right with probability one, and the photodetector on the bottom with probability zero.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Blocking one of the paths, or equivalently detecting the presence of a photon on a path eliminates interference between the paths: both photodetectors will be hit with probability 1/2.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This indicates that after the first beam splitter the photon does not take one path or another, but rather exists in a quantum superposition of the two paths.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A well-known thought experiment predicts that if particle detectors are positioned at the slits, showing through which slit a photon goes, the interference pattern will disappear.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This which-way experiment illustrates the complementarity principle that photons can behave as either particles or waves, but cannot be observed as both at the same time.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Despite the importance of this thought experiment in the history of quantum mechanics (for example, see the discussion on Einstein's version of this experiment), technically feasible realizations of this experiment were not proposed until the 1970s.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] (Naive implementations of the textbook thought experiment are not possible because photons cannot be detected without absorbing the photon.) Currently, multiple experiments have been performed illustrating various aspects of complementarity.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] An experiment performed in 1987 produced results that demonstrated that partial information could be obtained regarding which path a particle had taken without destroying the interference altogether.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This "wave-particle trade-off" takes the form of an inequality relating the visibility of the interference pattern and the distinguishability of the which-way paths.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Wheeler's delayed-choice experiments demonstrate that extracting "which path" information after a particle passes through the slits can seem to retroactively alter its previous behavior at the slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Quantum eraser experiments demonstrate that wave behavior can be restored by erasing or otherwise making permanently unavailable the "which path" information.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A simple do-it-at-home illustration of the quantum eraser phenomenon was given in an article in *Scientific American*.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If one sets polarizers before each slit with their axes orthogonal to each other, the interference pattern will be eliminated.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The polarizers can be considered as introducing which-path information to each beam.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Introducing a third polarizer in front of the detector with an axis of 45° relative to the other polarizers "erases" this information, allowing the interference pattern to reappear.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This can also be accounted for by considering the light to be a classical wave, and also when using circular polarizers and single photons.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Implementations of the polarizers using entangled photon pairs have no classical explanation.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In a highly publicized experiment in 2012, researchers claimed to have identified the path each particle had taken without any adverse effects at all on the interference pattern generated by the particles.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In order to do this, they used a setup such that particles coming to the screen were not from a point-like source, but from a source with two intensity maxima.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] However, commentators such as Svensson have pointed out that there is in fact no conflict between the weak measurements performed in this variant of the double-slit experiment and the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Weak measurement followed by post-selection did not allow simultaneous position and momentum measurements for each individual particle, but rather allowed measurement of the average trajectory of the particles that arrived at different positions.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In other words, the experimenters were creating a statistical map of the full trajectory landscape.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1967, Pfleegor and Mandel demonstrated two-source interference using two separate lasers as light sources.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] It was shown experimentally in 1972 that in a double-slit system where only one slit was open at any time, interference was nonetheless observed provided the path difference was such that the detected photon could have come from either slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The experimental conditions were such that the photon density in the system was much less than 1.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1991, Carnal and Mlynek performed the classic Young's double slit experiment with metastable helium atoms passing through micrometer-scale slits in gold foil.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 1999, a quantum interference experiment (using a diffraction grating, rather than two slits) was successfully performed with buckyball molecules (each of which comprises 60 carbon atoms).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A buckyball is large enough (diameter about 0.7 nm, nearly half a million times larger than a proton) to be seen in an electron microscope.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2002, an electron field emission source was used to demonstrate the double-slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In this experiment, a coherent electron wave was emitted from two closely located emission sites on the needle apex, which acted as double slits, splitting the wave into two coherent electron waves in a vacuum.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The interference pattern between the two electron waves could then be observed.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2017, researchers performed the double-slit experiment using light-induced field electron emitters.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] With this technique, emission sites can be optically selected on a scale of ten nanometers.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] By selectively deactivating (closing) one of the two emissions (slits), researchers were able to show that the interference pattern disappeared.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Eliel presented an experimental and theoretical study of the optical transmission of a thin metal screen perforated by two subwavelength slits, separated by many optical wavelengths.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The total intensity of the far-field double-slit pattern is shown to be reduced or enhanced as a function of the wavelength of the incident light beam.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2012, researchers at the University of Nebraska–Lincoln performed the double-slit experiment with electrons as described by Richard Feynman, using new instruments that allowed control of the transmission of the two slits and the monitoring of single-electron detection events.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Electrons were fired by an electron gun and passed through one or two slits of 62 nm wide × 4 μm tall.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2013, a quantum interference experiment (using diffraction gratings, rather than two slits) was successfully performed with molecules that each comprised 810 atoms (whose total mass was over 10,000 daltons).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In 2025, scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology performed a version of the double-slit experiment using atoms trapped in an optical lattice and forming a Mott insulator.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] After being released from the optical lattice these ultra-cold atoms have Heisenberg uncertainty limited momentum and position.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Single photons initially scatter from the atoms coherently and form optical interference pattern.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] As the wavepackets of the released atoms expand, the interference pattern disappears, confirming incoherent scattering.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The experiment demonstrates wave interference using only quantum atoms and photons.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Hydrodynamic analogs have been developed that can recreate various aspects of quantum mechanical systems, including single-particle interference through a double-slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] A silicone oil droplet, bouncing along the surface of a liquid, self-propels via resonant interactions with its own wave field.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The droplet gently sloshes the liquid with every bounce.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] At the same time, ripples from past bounces affect its course.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Behaviors mimicked via this hydrodynamic pilot-wave system include quantum single particle diffraction, tunneling, quantized orbits, orbital level splitting, spin, and multimodal statistics.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] It is also possible to infer uncertainty relations and exclusion principles.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Videos are available illustrating various features of this system.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] However, more complicated systems that involve two or more particles in superposition are not amenable to such a simple, classically intuitive explanation.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Accordingly, no hydrodynamic analog of entanglement has been developed.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Nevertheless, optical analogs are possible.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Similar results have been obtained classically on water waves.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Much of the behaviour of light can be modelled using classical wave theory.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The Huygens–Fresnel principle is one such model; it states that each point on a wavefront generates a secondary wavelet, and that the disturbance at any subsequent point can be found by summing the contributions of the individual wavelets at that point.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This summation needs to take into account the phase as well as the amplitude of the individual wavelets.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Only the intensity of a light field can be measured—this is proportional to the square of the amplitude.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In the double-slit experiment, the two slits are illuminated by the quasi-monochromatic light of a single laser.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If the width of the slits is small enough (much less than the wavelength of the laser light), the slits diffract the light into cylindrical waves.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] These two cylindrical wavefronts are superimposed, and the amplitude, and therefore the intensity, at any point in the combined wavefronts depends on both the magnitude and the phase of the two wavefronts.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The difference in phase between the two waves is determined by the difference in the distance travelled by the two waves.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If the viewing distance is large compared with the separation of the slits (the far field), the phase difference can be found using the geometry shown in the figure below right.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] where *d* is the distance between the two slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] where *λ* is the wavelength of the light.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] For example, if two slits are separated by 0.5 mm (*d*), and are illuminated with a 0.6 μm wavelength laser (λ), then at a distance of 1 m (*z*), the spacing of the fringes will be 1.2 mm.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] where the sinc function is defined as sinc(*x*) = sin(*x*)/*x* for *x* ≠ 0, and sinc(0) = 1.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The double-slit experiment can illustrate the path integral formulation of quantum mechanics provided by Feynman.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The path integral formulation replaces the classical notion of a single, unique trajectory for a system, with a sum over all possible trajectories.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The trajectories are added together by using functional integration.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Each path is considered equally likely, and thus contributes the same amount.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The probability distribution of the outcome is the normalized square of the norm of the superposition, over all paths from the point of origin to the final point, of waves propagating proportionally to the action along each path.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The differences in the cumulative action along the different paths (and thus the relative phases of the contributions) produces the interference pattern observed by the double-slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Feynman stressed that his formulation is merely a mathematical description, not an attempt to describe a real process that we can measure.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Like the Schrödinger's cat thought experiment, the double-slit experiment is often used to highlight the differences and similarities between the various interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The standard interpretation of the double slit experiment is that the pattern is a wave phenomenon, representing interference between two probability amplitudes, one for each slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Low intensity experiments demonstrate that the pattern is filled in one particle detection at a time.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Any change to the apparatus designed to detect a particle at a particular slit alters the probability amplitudes and the interference disappears.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This interpretation is independent of any conscious observer.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Niels Bohr interpreted quantum experiments like the double-slit experiment using the concept of complementarity.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In Bohr's view quantum systems are not classical, but measurements can only give classical results.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Certain pairs of classical properties will never be observed in a quantum system simultaneously: the interference pattern of waves in the double slit experiment will disappear if particles are detected at the slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Modern quantitative versions of the concept allow for a continuous tradeoff between the visibility of the interference fringes and the probability of particle detection at a slit.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The Copenhagen interpretation is a collection of views about the meaning of quantum mechanics, stemming from the work of Niels Bohr, Werner Heisenberg, Max Born, and others.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The term "Copenhagen interpretation" was apparently coined by Heisenberg during the 1950s to refer to ideas developed in the 1925–1927 period, glossing over his disagreements with Bohr.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Consequently, there is no definitive historical statement of what the interpretation entails.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Features common across versions of the Copenhagen interpretation include the idea that quantum mechanics is intrinsically indeterministic, with probabilities calculated using the Born rule, and some form of complementarity principle.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Moreover, the act of "observing" or "measuring" an object is irreversible, and no truth can be attributed to an object, except according to the results of its measurement.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In the Copenhagen interpretation, complementarity means a particular experiment can demonstrate particle behavior (passing through a definite slit) or wave behavior (interference), but not both at the same time.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In a Copenhagen-type view, the question of which slit a particle travels through has no meaning when there is no detector.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] In the case of an electron, if it is initially "observed" at a particular slit, then the observer–particle (photon–electron) interaction includes information about the electron's position.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This partially constrains the particle's eventual location at the screen.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] If it is "observed" (measured with a photon) not at a particular slit but rather at the screen, then there is no "which path" information as part of the interaction, so the electron's "observed" position on the screen is determined strictly by its probability function.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This makes the resulting pattern on the screen the same as if each individual electron had passed through both slits.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] As with Copenhagen, there are multiple variants of the many-worlds interpretation.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The unifying theme is that physical reality is identified with a wavefunction, and this wavefunction always evolves unitarily, i.e., following the Schrödinger equation with no collapses.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Consequently, there are many parallel universes, which only interact with each other through interference.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] David Deutsch argues that the way to understand the double-slit experiment is that in each universe the particle travels through a specific slit, but its motion is affected by interference with particles in other universes, and this interference creates the observable fringes.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] David Wallace, another advocate of the many-worlds interpretation, writes that in the familiar setup of the double-slit experiment the two paths are not sufficiently separated for a description in terms of parallel universes to make sense.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] An alternative to the standard understanding of quantum mechanics, the De Broglie–Bohm theory states that particles also have precise locations at all times, and that their velocities are defined by the wave-function.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] So while a single particle will travel through one particular slit in the double-slit experiment, the so-called "pilot wave" that influences it will travel through both.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] The two slit de Broglie–Bohm trajectories were first calculated by Chris Dewdney while working with Chris Philippidis and Basil Hiley at Birkbeck College (London).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Although de Broglie–Bohm theory overcomes many of the conceptual difficulties of quantum mechanics in the non-relativistic setting, it is incompatible with Lorentz invariance.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] 100 trajectories guided by the wave function.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] This is a kind of augmented reality compared to the standard interpretation.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Numerical simulation of the double-slit experiment with electrons.
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Figure on the left: evolution (from left to right) of the intensity of the electron beam at the exit of the slits (left) up to the detection screen located 10 cm after the slits (right).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Numerical data from Claus Jönsson's experiment (1961).
[src:wave-optics/double-slit-experiment] Photons, atoms and molecules follow a similar evolution.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] In contrast, the diffraction pattern created near the diffracting object and (in the near field region) is given by the Fresnel diffraction equation.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The equation was named in honor of Joseph von Fraunhofer although he was not actually involved in the development of the theory.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] This article explains where the Fraunhofer equation can be applied, and shows Fraunhofer diffraction patterns for various apertures.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] A detailed mathematical treatment of Fraunhofer diffraction is given in Fraunhofer diffraction equation.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] When a beam of light is partly blocked by an obstacle, some of the light is scattered around the object, light and dark bands are often seen at the edge of the shadow – this effect is a result of diffraction.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] When two light waves as electromagnetic fields are added together (vector sum), the amplitude of the wave sum depends on the amplitudes, the phases, and even the polarizations of individual waves.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Generally, a two-dimensional integral over complex variables has to be solved and in many cases, an analytic solution is not available.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] With a sufficiently distant light source from a diffracting aperture, the incident light to the aperture is effectively a plane wave so that the phase of the light at each point on the aperture is the same.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Even the amplitudes of the secondary waves coming from the aperture at the observation point can be treated as same or constant for a simple diffraction wave calculation in this case.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Diffraction in such a geometrical requirement is called *Fraunhofer diffraction*, and the condition where Fraunhofer diffraction is valid is called *Fraunhofer condition*, as shown in the right box.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] A diffracted wave is often called *Far field* if it at least partially satisfies Fraunhofer condition such that the distance between the aperture and the observation plane L is $L\gg {\frac {W^{2}}{\lambda }}$ .
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] For example, if a 0.5 mm diameter circular hole is illuminated by a laser light with 0.6 μm wavelength, then Fraunhofer diffraction occurs if the viewing distance is greater than 1000 mm.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The derivation of Fraunhofer condition here is based on the geometry described in the right box.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The geometrical implication from this expression is that the paths *r*2 and *r*1 are approximately parallel with each other.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] In each of these examples, the aperture is illuminated by a monochromatic plane wave at normal incidence.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The Fraunhofer diffraction pattern is shown in the image together with a plot of the intensity vs. angle θ.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The pattern has maximum intensity at *θ* = 0, and a series of peaks of decreasing intensity.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Most of the diffracted light falls between the first minima.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Thus, the smaller the aperture, the larger the angle α subtended by the diffraction bands.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] For example, when a slit of width 0.5 mm is illuminated by light of wavelength 0.6 μm, and viewed at a distance of 1000 mm, the width of the central band in the diffraction pattern is 2.4 mm.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The fringes extend to infinity in the *y* direction since the slit and illumination also extend to infinity.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] If W < λ, the intensity of the diffracted light does not fall to zero, and if $D\ll \lambda$ , the diffracted wave is cylindrical.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] We can find the angle at which a first minimum is obtained in the diffracted light by the following reasoning.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Consider the light diffracted at an angle θ where the distance *CD* is equal to the wavelength of the illuminating light.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The width of the slit is the distance *AC*.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The component of the wavelet emitted from the point A which is travelling in the θ direction is in anti-phase with the wave from the point *B* at middle of the slit, so that the net contribution at the angle θ from these two waves is zero.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The same applies to the points just below *A* and *B*, and so on.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Therefore, the amplitude of the total wave travelling in the direction θ is zero.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] There is no such simple argument to enable us to find the maxima of the diffraction pattern.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] We can develop an expression for the far field of a continuous array of point sources of uniform amplitude and of the same phase.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Let the array of length *a* be parallel to the y axis with its center at the origin as indicated in the figure to the right.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The form of the diffraction pattern given by a rectangular aperture is shown in the figure on the right (or above, in tablet format).
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] There is a central semi-rectangular peak, with a series of horizontal and vertical fringes.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The dimensions of the central band are related to the dimensions of the slit by the same relationship as for a single slit so that the larger dimension in the diffracted image corresponds to the smaller dimension in the slit.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The spacing of the fringes is also inversely proportional to the slit dimension.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] If the illuminating beam does not illuminate the whole vertical length of the slit, the spacing of the vertical fringes is determined by the dimensions of the illuminating beam.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Close examination of the double-slit diffraction pattern below shows that there are very fine horizontal diffraction fringes above and below the main spot, as well as the more obvious horizontal fringes.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The diffraction pattern given by a circular aperture is shown in the figure on the right.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] This is known as the Airy diffraction pattern.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] It can be seen that most of the light is in the central disk.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] $\alpha \approx {\frac {1.22\lambda }{W}}$ where *W* is the diameter of the aperture.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The Airy disk can be an important parameter in limiting the ability of an imaging system to resolve closely located objects.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The diffraction pattern obtained given by an aperture with a Gaussian profile, for example, a photographic slide whose transmissivity has a Gaussian variation is also a Gaussian function.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The form of the function is plotted on the right (above, for a tablet), and it can be seen that, unlike the diffraction patterns produced by rectangular or circular apertures, it has no secondary rings.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] This technique can be used in a process called apodization—the aperture is covered by a Gaussian filter, giving a diffraction pattern with no secondary rings.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The output profile of a single mode laser beam may have a Gaussian intensity profile and the diffraction equation can be used to show that it maintains that profile however far away it propagates from the source.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] In the double-slit experiment, the two slits are illuminated by a single light beam.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] If the width of the slits is small enough (less than the wavelength of the light), the slits diffract the light into cylindrical waves.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] These fringes are often known as Young's fringes.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The spacing of the fringes at a distance z from the slits is given by $w_{\text{f}}=z\theta _{f}=z\lambda /d,$ where d is the separation of the slits.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The fringes in the picture were obtained using the yellow light from a sodium light (wavelength = 589 nm), with slits separated by 0.25 mm, and projected directly onto the image plane of a digital camera.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] Double-slit interference fringes can be observed by cutting two slits in a piece of card, illuminating with a laser pointer, and observing the diffracted light at a distance of 1 m.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] If the slit separation is 0.5 mm, and the wavelength of the laser is 600 nm, then the spacing of the fringes viewed at a distance of 1 m would be 1.2 mm.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] If the viewing distance is large compared with the separation of the slits (the far field), the phase difference can be found using the geometry shown in the figure.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The interference fringe maxima occur at angles $d\theta _{n}=n\lambda ,\quad n=0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\ldots$ where λ is the wavelength of the light.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] A grating is defined in Born and Wolf as "any arrangement which imposes on an incident wave a periodic variation of amplitude or phase, or both".
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The finer the grating spacing, the greater the angular separation of the diffracted beams.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The detailed structure of the repeating pattern determines the form of the individual diffracted beams, as well as their relative intensity while the grating spacing always determines the angles of the diffracted beams.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The image on the right shows a laser beam diffracted by a grating into *n* = 0, and ±1 beams.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] The angles of the first order beams are about 20°; if we assume the wavelength of the laser beam is 600 nm, we can infer that the grating spacing is about 1.8 μm.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] A simple grating consists of a series of slits in a screen.
[src:wave-optics/fraunhofer-diffraction] This is the same relationship that is given above.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In optics, the **Fresnel diffraction** equation for **near-field diffraction** is an approximation of the Kirchhoff–Fresnel diffraction that can be applied to the propagation of waves in the near field.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] It is used to calculate the diffraction pattern created by waves passing through an aperture or around an object, when viewed from relatively close to the object.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In contrast the diffraction pattern in the far field region is given by the Fraunhofer diffraction equation.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The near field can be specified by the Fresnel number, *F*, of the optical arrangement.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] When $F\ll 1$ the diffracted wave is considered to be in the Fraunhofer field.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] However, the validity of the Fresnel diffraction integral is deduced by the approximations derived below.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] where $\theta$ is the maximal angle described by $\theta \approx a/L,$ *a* and *L* the same as in the definition of the Fresnel number.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Hence this condition can be approximated as ${\textstyle {\frac {a^{4}}{4L^{3}\lambda }}\ll 1}$ .
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The multiple Fresnel diffraction at closely spaced periodical ridges (ridged mirror) causes the specular reflection; this effect can be used for atomic mirrors.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Some of the earliest work on what would become known as Fresnel diffraction was carried out by Francesco Maria Grimaldi in Italy in the 17th century.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In his monograph entitled "Light", Richard C.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] MacLaurin explains Fresnel diffraction by asking what happens when light propagates, and how that process is affected when a barrier with a slit or hole in it is interposed in the beam produced by a distant source of light.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] He uses the Principle of Huygens to investigate, in classical terms, what transpires.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The wave front that proceeds from the slit and on to a detection screen some distance away very closely approximates a wave front originating across the area of the gap without regard to any minute interactions with the actual physical edge.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The result is that if the gap is very narrow only diffraction patterns with bright centers can occur.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] If the gap is made progressively wider, then diffraction patterns with dark centers will alternate with diffraction patterns with bright centers.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] As the gap becomes larger, the differentials between dark and light bands decrease until a diffraction effect can no longer be detected.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] MacLaurin does not mention the possibility that the center of the series of diffraction rings produced when light is shone through a small hole may be black, but he does point to the inverse situation wherein the shadow produced by a small circular object can paradoxically have a bright center.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In his *Optics*, Francis Weston Sears offers a mathematical approximation suggested by Fresnel that predicts the main features of diffraction patterns and uses only simple mathematics.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] By considering the perpendicular distance from the hole in a barrier screen to a nearby detection screen along with the wavelength of the incident light, it is possible to compute a number of regions called half-period elements or Fresnel zones.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The inner zone is a circle and each succeeding zone will be a concentric annular ring.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] If the diameter of the circular hole in the screen is sufficient to expose the first or central Fresnel zone, the amplitude of light at the center of the detection screen will be double what it would be if the detection screen were not obstructed.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] If the diameter of the circular hole in the screen is sufficient to expose two Fresnel zones, then the amplitude at the center is almost zero.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] That means that a Fresnel diffraction pattern can have a dark center.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] These patterns can be seen and measured, and correspond well to the values calculated for them.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The analytical solution of this integral quickly becomes impractically complex for all but the simplest diffraction geometries.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Therefore, it is usually calculated numerically.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The main problem for solving the integral is the expression of *r*.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] If we consider all the terms of binomial series, then there is no approximation.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Let us substitute this expression in the argument of the exponential within the integral; the key to the Fresnel approximation is to assume that the third term is very small and can be ignored, and henceforth any higher orders.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In order to make this possible, it has to contribute to the variation of the exponential for an almost null term.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] If this condition holds true for all values of x, x', y and y', then we can ignore the third term in the Taylor expression.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Furthermore, if the third term is negligible, then all terms of higher order will be even smaller, so we can ignore them as well.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] For applications involving optical wavelengths, the wavelength λ is typically many orders of magnitude smaller than the relevant physical dimensions.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] This equation is the **Fresnel approximation**, and the inequality stated above is a condition for the approximation's validity.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The condition for validity is fairly weak, and it allows all length parameters to take comparable values, provided the aperture is small compared to the path length.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] For the r in the denominator we go one step further and approximate it with only the first term, $r\approx z.$ This is valid in particular if we are interested in the behaviour of the field only in a small area close to the origin, where the values of x and y are much smaller than z.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] In general, Fresnel diffraction is valid if the Fresnel number is approximately 1.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] This is the Fresnel diffraction integral; it means that, if the Fresnel approximation is valid, the propagating field is a spherical wave, originating at the aperture and moving along z.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The integral modulates the amplitude and phase of the spherical wave.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Analytical solution of this expression is still only possible in rare cases.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] For a further simplified case, valid only for much larger distances from the diffraction source, see Fraunhofer diffraction.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Unlike Fraunhofer diffraction, Fresnel diffraction accounts for the curvature of the wavefront, in order to correctly calculate the relative phase of interfering waves.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] The integral can be expressed in other ways in order to calculate it using some mathematical properties.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] in other words, we are representing the propagation using a linear-filter modeling.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] That is why we might call the function $h(x,y,z)$ the impulse response of free-space propagation.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] Another possible way is through the Fourier transform.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] then we can express the integral in terms of the two-dimensional Fourier transform.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] where p and q are spatial frequencies (wavenumbers).
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] That is, first multiply the field to be propagated by a complex exponential, calculate its two-dimensional Fourier transform, replace $(p,q)$ with $\left({\tfrac {x}{\lambda z}},{\tfrac {y}{\lambda z}}\right)$ and multiply it by another factor.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] This expression is better than the others when the process leads to a known Fourier transform, and the connection with the Fourier transform is tightened in the linear canonical transformation, discussed below.
[src:wave-optics/fresnel-diffraction] From the point of view of the linear canonical transformation, Fresnel diffraction can be seen as a shear in the time–frequency domain, corresponding to how the Fourier transform is a rotation in the time–frequency domain.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The **Huygens–Fresnel principle** (named after Dutch physicist Christiaan Huygens and French physicist Augustin-Jean Fresnel) states that every point on a wavefront is itself the source of spherical wavelets and that the secondary wavelets emanating from different points mutually interfere.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The sum of these spherical wavelets forms a new wavefront.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] As such, the Huygens–Fresnel principle is a method of analysis applied to problems of luminous wave propagation both in the far-field limit and in near-field diffraction as well as reflection.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In 1678, Huygens proposed that every point reached by a luminous disturbance becomes a source of a spherical wave.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The sum of these secondary waves determines the form of the wave at any subsequent time; the overall procedure is referred to as **Huygens's construction**.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] He assumed that the secondary waves traveled only in the "forward" direction, but it is not explained in the theory why this is the case.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In 1818, Fresnel showed that Huygens's principle, together with his own principle of interference, could explain both the rectilinear propagation of light and also diffraction effects.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] To obtain agreement with the experimental results, he had to include additional arbitrary assumptions about the phase and amplitude of the secondary waves, as well as an obliquity factor.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] These assumptions have no obvious physical foundation, but led to predictions that agreed with many experimental observations, including the Poisson spot.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Poisson was a member of the French Academy, which reviewed Fresnel's work.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] He used Fresnel's theory to predict that a bright spot ought to appear in the center of the shadow of a small disc, and deduced from this that the theory was incorrect.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] However, François Arago, another member of the committee, performed the experiment and showed that the prediction was correct.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] This success was important evidence in favor of the wave theory of light over then predominant corpuscular theory.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In 1882, Gustav Kirchhoff analyzed Fresnel's theory in a rigorous mathematical formulation, as an approximate form of an integral theorem.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Very few rigorous solutions to diffraction problems are known, however, and most problems in optics are adequately treated using the Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In 1939 Edward Copson, extended Huygens's original principle to consider the polarization of light, which requires a vector potential, in contrast to the scalar potential of a simple ocean wave or sound wave.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In antenna theory and engineering, the reformulation of the Huygens–Fresnel principle for radiating current sources is known as surface equivalence principle.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Issues in Huygens–Fresnel theory continue to be of interest.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Miller suggested that treating the source as a dipole (not the monopole assumed by Huygens) will cancel waves propagating in the reverse direction, making Huygens's construction quantitatively correct.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Anderson showed that treating the wavelets as Dirac delta functions, summing and differentiating the summation is sufficient to cancel reverse propagating waves.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The apparent change in direction of a light ray as it enters a sheet of glass at an angle can be understood by the Huygens's construction.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Each point on the surface of the glass gives a secondary wavelet.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] These wavelets propagate at a slower velocity in the glass, making less forward progress than their counterparts in air.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] When the wavelets are summed, the resulting wavefront propagates at an angle to the direction of the wavefront in air.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In an inhomogeneous medium with a variable index of refraction, different parts of the wavefront propagate at different speeds.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Consequently, the wavefront bends around in the direction of the higher index.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The Huygens–Fresnel principle provides a reasonable basis for understanding and predicting the classical wave propagation of light.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] However, there are limitations to the principle, namely the same approximations made for deriving the Kirchhoff's diffraction formula and the approximations of near field due to Fresnel.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] These can be summarized in the fact that the wavelength of light is much smaller than the dimensions of any optical components encountered.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Kirchhoff's diffraction formula provides a rigorous mathematical foundation for diffraction, based on the wave equation.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The arbitrary assumptions made by Fresnel to arrive at the Huygens–Fresnel equation emerge automatically from the mathematics in this derivation.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] A simple example of the operation of the principle can be observed when an open doorway connects two rooms and a sound is produced in a remote corner of one of them.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] A person in the other room will hear the sound as if it originated at the doorway.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] As far as the second room is concerned, the vibrating air in the doorway is the source of the sound.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Consider the case of a point source located at a point **P**0, vibrating at a frequency *f*.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The disturbance may be described by a complex variable *U*0 known as the complex amplitude.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] It produces a spherical wave with wavelength λ, wavenumber *k* = 2*π*/*λ*.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Note that magnitude decreases in inverse proportion to the distance traveled, and the phase changes as *k* times the distance traveled.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Using Huygens's theory and the principle of superposition of waves, the complex amplitude at a further point **P** is found by summing the contribution from each point on the sphere of radius *r*0.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In order to obtain agreement with experimental results, Fresnel found that the individual contributions from the secondary waves on the sphere had to be multiplied by a constant, −*i*/λ, and by an additional inclination factor, *K*(χ).
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The first assumption implies that the secondary waves oscillate at a quarter of a cycle out of phase with respect to the primary wave and the second implies that the magnitude of the secondary waves is in a ratio of 1:λ to the primary wave.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] He also assumed that *K*(χ) had a maximum value when χ = 0, and was equal to zero when χ = π/2, where χ is the angle between the normal of the primary wavefront and the normal of the secondary wavefront.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] where *S* describes the surface of the sphere, and *s* is the distance between **Q** and **P**.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Fresnel used a zone construction method to find approximate values of *K* for the different zones, which enabled him to make predictions that were in agreement with experimental results.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The integral theorem of Kirchhoff includes the basic idea of Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Kirchhoff showed that in many cases, the theorem can be approximated to a simpler form that is equivalent to the formation of Fresnel's formulation.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The above derivation of *K*(χ) assumed that the diffracting aperture is illuminated by a single spherical wave with a sufficiently large radius of curvature.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] However, the principle holds for more general illuminations.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] An arbitrary illumination can be decomposed into a collection of point sources, and the linearity of the wave equation can be invoked to apply the principle to each point source individually.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In this case, *K* satisfies the conditions stated above (maximum value at χ = 0 and zero at χ = π/2).
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] where *G* is known as the Green's function or *propagator*, which propagates the wave function $\psi$ in time.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] This generalized principle is the basis for Feynman's approach to quantum electrodynamics.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Huygens's theory served as a fundamental explanation of the wave nature of light interference and was further developed by Fresnel and Young, but did not fully resolve all observations, such as the low-intensity double-slit experiment first performed by G.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] It was not until the early and mid-1900s that quantum theory discussions, particularly the early discussions at the 1927 Brussels Solvay Conference, where Louis de Broglie proposed his de Broglie hypothesis that the photon is guided by a wave function.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The wave function presents a much different explanation of the observed light and dark bands in a double slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In this conception, the photon follows a path that is a probabilistic choice of one of many possible paths in the electromagnetic field.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] These probable paths form the pattern: in dark areas, no photons are landing, and in bright areas, many photons are landing.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The set of possible photon paths is consistent with Richard Feynman's path integral theory, the paths determined by the surroundings: the photon's originating point (atom), the slit, and the screen and by tracking and summing phases.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The wave function is a solution to this geometry.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The wave function approach was further supported by additional double-slit experiments in Italy and Japan in the 1970s and 1980s with electrons.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Huygens's principle can be seen as a consequence of the homogeneity of space—space is uniform in all locations.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Any disturbance created in a sufficiently small region of homogeneous space (or in a homogeneous medium) propagates from that region in all geodesic directions.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The waves produced by this disturbance, in turn, create disturbances in other regions, and so on.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The superposition of all the waves results in the observed pattern of wave propagation.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Homogeneity of space is fundamental to quantum field theory (QFT), where the wave function of any object propagates along all available unobstructed paths.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] When integrated along all possible paths, with a phase factor proportional to the action, the interference of the wave-functions correctly predicts observable phenomena.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] Every point on the wavefront acts as the source of secondary wavelets that spread out in the light cone with the same speed as the wave.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The new wavefront is found by constructing the surface tangent to the secondary wavelets.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In 1900, Jacques Hadamard observed that Huygens's principle was broken when the number of spatial dimensions is even.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] From this, he developed a set of conjectures that remain an active topic of research.
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] In particular, it has been discovered that Huygens's principle holds on a large class of homogeneous spaces derived from the Coxeter group (so, for example, the Weyl groups of simple Lie algebras).
[src:wave-optics/huygens-fresnel-principle] The traditional statement of Huygens's principle for the d'Alembertian gives rise to the KdV hierarchy; analogously, the Dirac operator gives rise to the AKNS hierarchy.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In physics, **interference** is a phenomenon in which two coherent waves are combined by adding their intensities or displacements with due consideration for their phase difference.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The resultant wave may have greater amplitude (**constructive interference**) or lower amplitude (**destructive interference**) if the two waves are in phase or out of phase, respectively.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interference effects can be observed with all types of waves, for example, light, radio, acoustic, surface water waves, gravity waves, or matter waves as well as in loudspeakers as electrical waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Around 1800, the word *interference* was used by Thomas Young in developing his theories of acoustics and optics.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The principle of superposition of waves states that when two or more propagating waves of the same type are incident on the same point, the resultant amplitude at that point is equal to the vector sum of the amplitudes of the individual waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If a crest of a wave meets a crest of another wave of the same frequency at the same point, then the amplitude is the sum of the individual amplitudes—this is **constructive interference**.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If a crest of one wave meets a trough of another wave, then the amplitude is equal to the difference in the individual amplitudes—this is known as **destructive interference**.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In ideal mediums (water, air are almost ideal) energy is always conserved, at points of destructive interference, the wave amplitudes cancel each other out, and the energy is redistributed to other areas.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] For example, when two pebbles are dropped in a pond, a pattern is observable; but eventually waves continue, and only when they reach the shore is the energy absorbed away from the medium.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Constructive interference occurs when the phase difference between the waves is an **even multiple** of π (180°), whereas destructive interference occurs when the difference is an **odd multiple** of π.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If the difference between the phases is intermediate between these two extremes, then the magnitude of the displacement of the summed waves lies between the minimum and maximum values.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Consider, for example, what happens when two identical stones are dropped into a still pool of water at different locations.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Each stone generates a circular wave propagating outwards from the point where the stone was dropped.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] When the two waves overlap, the net displacement at a particular point is the sum of the displacements of the individual waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] At some points, these will be in phase, and will produce a maximum displacement.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In other places, the waves will be in anti-phase, and there will be no net displacement at these points.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Thus, parts of the surface will be stationary—these are seen in the figure above and to the right as stationary blue-green lines radiating from the centre.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interference of light is a unique phenomenon in that we can never observe superposition of the EM field directly as we can, for example, in water.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Superposition in the EM field is an assumed phenomenon and necessary to explain how two light beams pass through each other and continue on their respective paths.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Prime examples of light interference are the famous double-slit experiment, laser speckle, anti-reflective coatings and interferometers.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In addition to the classical wave model for understanding optical interference, quantum matter waves also demonstrate interference.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The above can be demonstrated in one dimension by deriving the formula for the sum of two waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The equation for the amplitude of a sinusoidal wave traveling to the right along the x-axis is $W_{1}(x,t)=A\cos(kx-\omega t)$ where A is the peak amplitude, $k=2\pi /\lambda$ is the wavenumber and $\omega =2\pi f$ is the angular frequency of the wave.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Suppose a second wave of the same frequency and amplitude but with a different phase is also traveling to the right $W_{2}(x,t)=A\cos(kx-\omega t+\varphi )$ where $\varphi$ is the phase difference between the waves in radians.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A simple form of interference pattern is obtained if two plane waves of the same frequency intersect at an angle.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] One wave is travelling horizontally, and the other is travelling downwards at an angle θ to the first wave.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Assuming that the two waves are in phase at the point **B**, then the relative phase changes along the *x*-axis.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Constructive interference occurs when the waves are in phase, and destructive interference when they are half a cycle out of phase.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] and *df* is known as the fringe spacing.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The fringe spacing increases with increase in wavelength, and with decreasing angle θ.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The fringes are observed wherever the two waves overlap and the fringe spacing is uniform throughout.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A point source produces a spherical wave.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If the light from two point sources overlaps, the interference pattern maps out the way in which the phase difference between the two waves varies in space.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This depends on the wavelength and on the separation of the point sources.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The figure to the right shows interference between two spherical waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The wavelength increases from top to bottom, and the distance between the sources increases from left to right.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] When the plane of observation is far enough away, the fringe pattern will be a series of almost straight lines, since the waves will then be almost planar.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interference occurs when several waves are added together provided that the phase differences between them remain constant over the observation time.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] It is sometimes desirable for several waves of the same frequency and amplitude to sum to zero (that is, interfere destructively, cancel).
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This is the principle behind, for example, 3-phase power and the diffraction grating.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In both of these cases, the result is achieved by uniform spacing of the phases.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] It is easy to see that a set of waves will cancel if they have the same amplitude and their phases are spaced equally in angle.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The Fabry–Pérot interferometer uses interference between multiple reflections.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A diffraction grating can be considered to be a multiple-beam interferometer; since the peaks which it produces are generated by interference between the light transmitted by each of the elements in the grating; see interference vs. diffraction for further discussion.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Because the frequency of light waves (~1014 Hz) is too high for currently available detectors to detect the variation of the electric field of the light, it is possible to observe only the intensity of an optical interference pattern.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The intensity of the light at a given point is proportional to the square of the average amplitude of the wave.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This can be expressed mathematically as follows.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] where A represents the magnitude of the displacement, φ represents the phase and ω represents the angular frequency.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Thus, the interference pattern maps out the difference in phase between the two waves, with maxima occurring when the phase difference is a multiple of 2π.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If the two beams are of equal intensity, the maxima are four times as bright as the individual beams, and the minima have zero intensity.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Classically the two waves must have the same polarization to give rise to interference fringes since it is not possible for waves of different polarizations to cancel one another out or add together.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Instead, when waves of different polarization are added together, they give rise to a wave of a different polarization state.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Quantum mechanically the theories of Paul Dirac and Richard Feynman offer a more modern approach.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Dirac showed that every quanta or photon of light acts on its own which he famously stated as "every photon interferes with itself".
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Richard Feynman showed that by evaluating a path integral where all possible paths are considered, that a number of higher probability paths will emerge.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In thin films for example, film thickness which is not a multiple of light wavelength will not allow the quanta to traverse, only reflection is possible.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The discussion above assumes that the waves which interfere with one another are monochromatic, i.e. have a single frequency—this requires that they are infinite in time.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This is not, however, either practical or necessary.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Two identical waves of finite duration whose frequency is fixed over that period will give rise to an interference pattern while they overlap.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Conventional light sources emit waves of differing frequencies and at different times from different points in the source.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If the light is split into two waves and then re-combined, each individual light wave may generate an interference pattern with its other half, but the individual fringe patterns generated will have different phases and spacings, and normally no overall fringe pattern will be observable.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] However, single-element light sources, such as sodium- or mercury-vapor lamps have emission lines with quite narrow frequency spectra.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] When these are spatially and colour filtered, and then split into two waves, they can be superimposed to generate interference fringes.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] All interferometry prior to the invention of the laser was done using such sources and had a wide range of successful applications.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A laser beam generally approximates much more closely to a monochromatic source, and thus it is much more straightforward to generate interference fringes using a laser.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The ease with which interference fringes can be observed with a laser beam can sometimes cause problems in that stray reflections may give spurious interference fringes which can result in errors.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Normally, a single laser beam is used in interferometry, though interference has been observed using two independent lasers whose frequencies were sufficiently matched to satisfy the phase requirements.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This has also been observed for widefield interference between two incoherent laser sources.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] It is also possible to observe interference fringes using white light.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A white light fringe pattern can be considered to be made up of a 'spectrum' of fringe patterns each of slightly different spacing.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If all the fringe patterns are in phase in the centre, then the fringes will increase in size as the wavelength decreases and the summed intensity will show three to four fringes of varying colour.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Young describes this very elegantly in his discussion of two slit interference.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Since white light fringes are obtained only when the two waves have travelled equal distances from the light source, they can be very useful in interferometry, as they allow the zero path difference fringe to be identified.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] To generate interference fringes, light from the source has to be divided into two waves which then have to be re-combined.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Traditionally, interferometers have been classified as either amplitude-division or wavefront-division systems.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In an amplitude-division system, a beam splitter is used to divide the light into two beams travelling in different directions, which are then superimposed to produce the interference pattern.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The Michelson interferometer and the Mach–Zehnder interferometer are examples of amplitude-division systems.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In wavefront-division systems, the wave is divided in space—examples are Young's double slit interferometer and Lloyd's mirror.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interference can also be seen in everyday phenomena such as iridescence and structural coloration.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] For example, the colours seen in a soap bubble arise from interference of light reflecting off the front and back surfaces of the thin soap film.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Depending on the thickness of the film, different colours interfere constructively and destructively.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Usually, $\Psi _{A}(x,t)$ and $\Psi _{B}(x,t)$ correspond to distinct situations A and B.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] When this is the case, the equation $\Psi (x,t)=\Psi _{A}(x,t)+\Psi _{B}(x,t)$ indicates that the object can be in situation A or situation B.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The above equation can then be interpreted as: The probability of finding the object at x is the probability of finding the object at x when it is in situation A plus the probability of finding the object at x when it is in situation B plus an extra term.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This extra term, which is called the *quantum interference term*, is $\Psi _{A}^{*}(x,t)\Psi _{B}(x,t)+\Psi _{A}(x,t)\Psi _{B}^{*}(x,t)$ in the above equation.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] As in the classical wave case above, the quantum interference term can add (constructive interference) or subtract (destructive interference) from $|\Psi _{A}(x,t)|^{2}+|\Psi _{B}(x,t)|^{2}$ in the above equation depending on whether the quantum interference term is positive or negative.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] If this term is absent for all x , then there is no quantum mechanical interference associated with situations A and B.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The best known example of quantum interference is the double-slit experiment.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In this experiment, matter waves from electrons, atoms or molecules approach a barrier with two slits in it.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The part of the wavefunction going through one slit is associated with $\Psi _{A}(x,t)$ while the part going through the other slit is associated with $\Psi _{B}(x,t)$ .
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The interference pattern occurs on the far side, observed by detectors suitable to the particles originating the matter wave.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The pattern matches the optical double slit pattern.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In acoustics, a **beat** is an interference pattern between two sounds of slightly different frequencies, *perceived* as a periodic variation in volume whose rate is the difference of the two frequencies.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] With tuning instruments that can produce sustained tones, beats can be readily recognized.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Tuning two tones to a unison will present a peculiar effect: when the two tones are close in pitch but not identical, the difference in frequency generates the beating.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The volume varies like in a tremolo as the sounds alternately interfere constructively and destructively.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] As the two tones gradually approach unison, the beating slows down and may become so slow as to be imperceptible.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] As the two tones get further apart, their beat frequency starts to approach the range of human pitch perception, the beating starts to sound like a note, and a combination tone is produced.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This combination tone can also be referred to as a missing fundamental, as the beat frequency of any two tones is equivalent to the frequency of their implied fundamental frequency.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interferometry is an experimental technique for measuring or using interference.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] It can be used with many types of waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] All interferometers require a source of coherent waves.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The simplest interferometer has a pinhole to create a coherent source followed by a mask with two holes and a screen to observe the interference.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Modern versions replace the initial pinhole with the coherent light of a laser.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Other wave-front splitting interferometers use mirror or prisms to split and recombine waves; amplitude splitting devices use thin dielectric films.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Multiple beam interferometers can include lenses.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The results of the Michelson–Morley experiment are generally considered to be the first strong evidence against the theory of a luminiferous aether and in favor of special relativity.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interferometry has been used in defining and calibrating length standards.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] When the metre was defined as the distance between two marks on a platinum-iridium bar, Michelson and Benoît used interferometry to measure the wavelength of the red cadmium line in the new standard, and also showed that it could be used as a length standard.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Sixty years later, in 1960, the metre in the new SI system was defined to be equal to 1,650,763.73 wavelengths of the orange-red emission line in the electromagnetic spectrum of the krypton-86 atom in a vacuum.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This definition was replaced in 1983 by defining the metre as the distance travelled by light in vacuum during a specific time interval.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interferometry is still fundamental in establishing the calibration chain in length measurement.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interferometry is used in the calibration of slip gauges (called gauge blocks in the US) and in coordinate-measuring machines.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] It is also used in the testing of optical components.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] In 1946, a technique called astronomical interferometry was developed.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Astronomical radio interferometers usually consist either of arrays of parabolic dishes or two-dimensional arrays of omni-directional antennas.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] All of the telescopes in the array are widely separated and are usually connected together using coaxial cable, waveguide, optical fiber, or other type of transmission line.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] Interferometry increases the total signal collected, but its primary purpose is to vastly increase the resolution through a process called Aperture synthesis.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This technique works by superposing (interfering) the signal waves from the different telescopes on the principle that waves that coincide with the same phase will add to each other while two waves that have opposite phases will cancel each other out.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] This creates a combined telescope that is equivalent in resolution (though not in sensitivity) to a single antenna whose diameter is equal to the spacing of the antennas farthest apart in the array.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] An acoustic interferometer is an instrument for measuring the physical characteristics of sound waves in a gas or liquid, such as velocity, wavelength, absorption, or impedance.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] A vibrating crystal creates ultrasonic waves that are radiated into the medium.
[src:wave-optics/wave-interference] The waves strike a reflector placed parallel to the crystal, reflected back to the source and measured.
